&gt;   2008/9/17 Jan Kroeze &lt;thejcwk@... &lt;thejcwk%40gmail.com&gt;&gt;:
&gt; &gt; Hi!
&gt; &gt;
&gt;
&gt; &gt; I think I understand your point #1, but I&#39;m not quite sure. Why was it
&gt; &gt; difficult to locate the specific tests?
&gt;
&gt; FIT lets you mix tests and freeform text, write documents that link to
&gt; tests, index tests in different ways, etc. etc. That&#39;s harder to do
&gt; with JUnit. We could have linked from our wiki to JUnit tests in
&gt; Subversion, which would have helped but made refactoring more
&gt; difficult.
&gt;
&gt; &gt; Your second point has been mentioned by quite a few people on the list.
&gt; &gt; Would I be correct if I thought of this factor as a major factor in
&gt; making
&gt; &gt; the decision to migrate to FIT or something similar?
&gt;
&gt; It&#39;s one of many factors. Refactoring and tool support are also
&gt; factors to take into account.
&gt;
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; 2008/9/14 Nat Pryce &lt;nat.pryce@... &lt;nat.pryce%40gmail.com&gt;&gt;
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt;&gt; I&#39;ve used JUnit for system testing as well as unit testing.
&gt; &gt;&gt;
&gt; &gt;&gt; It worked pretty well -- JUnit has great tool support, is small and
&gt; &gt;&gt; simple and, being plain old Java, is easy to extend or plug onto
&gt; &gt;&gt; existing APIs and external systems.
&gt; &gt;&gt;
&gt; &gt;&gt; The two main drawbacks we found were:
&gt; &gt;&gt;
&gt; &gt;&gt; 1) Too hard to go back and find out about the system behaviour from
&gt; &gt;&gt; the tests. We refactored our tests agressively into a &quot;domain
&gt; &gt;&gt; specific embedded language&quot; for describing business rules, but it was
&gt; &gt;&gt; difficult to find the test(s) we needed to read to understand why the
&gt; &gt;&gt; system did what it did.
&gt; &gt;&gt;
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt;&gt;
&gt; &gt;&gt; 2) A JUnit test aborts completely on failure. For system tests, we
&gt; &gt;&gt; wanted to distinguish between fatal failures that should abort the
&gt; &gt;&gt; test, and failures that allowed the test to continue running. For
&gt; &gt;&gt; example, a system that displays calculations in a table should fail
&gt; &gt;&gt; the test if any calculations are incorrect and report *all* the
&gt; &gt;&gt; incorrect calculations, not abort as soon as it detects a single
&gt; &gt;&gt; incorrect calculation.
&gt; &gt;&gt;
&gt; &gt;&gt; FIT and similar tools address these issues much better than JUnit, but
&gt; &gt;&gt; you sacrifice easy refactoring.
&gt; &gt;&gt;
&gt; &gt;&gt; --Nat
