&gt; &gt;&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt;&gt; &gt;&gt; Hi Jan,
&gt; &gt;&gt; &gt;&gt;
&gt; &gt;&gt; &gt;&gt; I agree, and as you touch on the idea of acceptance tests, you come
&gt; &gt;&gt; &gt;&gt; close to the one point I&#39;d add. Besides running time and number of
&gt; &gt;&gt; &gt;&gt; failures, the other distinguishing feature of acceptance tests is
&gt; that
&gt; &gt;&gt; &gt;&gt; the interacts often cross the system&#39;s boundary. By that I mean input
&gt; &gt;&gt; &gt;&gt; comes through non-java interfaces such as GUIs, message systems, etc.
&gt; &gt;&gt; &gt;&gt; and output involve more side effects (i.e. go to places other than
&gt; &gt;&gt; &gt;&gt; back to the source). In some cases, these can be shoehorned into a
&gt; &gt;&gt; &gt;&gt; Java interface (e.g. httpunit) but this is often where the need for
&gt; &gt;&gt; &gt;&gt; other tools comes in.
&gt; &gt;&gt; &gt;&gt;
&gt; &gt;&gt; &gt;&gt; The reason for fine-grained testing is that large-grained tests are
&gt; &gt;&gt; &gt;&gt; overwhelmed by combinatoric explosion of conditions long before they
&gt; &gt;&gt; &gt;&gt; achieve reasonable coverage. The &quot;unit&quot; is usually a single class.
&gt; &gt;&gt; &gt;&gt; The system can be tens to thousands of classes. For small systems,
&gt; &gt;&gt; &gt;&gt; the gap may be small enough that unit and acceptance tests are
&gt; &gt;&gt; &gt;&gt; sufficient.
&gt; &gt;&gt; &gt;&gt;
&gt; &gt;&gt; &gt;&gt; Often, however, it is useful to have integration tests in between. By
&gt; &gt;&gt; &gt;&gt; testing clusters of collaborating classes, integration tests can
&gt; &gt;&gt; &gt;&gt; further reduce the number of acceptance tests needed to achieve
&gt; &gt;&gt; &gt;&gt; reasonable coverage. The thing integration tests have in common with
&gt; &gt;&gt; &gt;&gt; unit tests is that by being entirely within the system boundary, they
&gt; &gt;&gt; &gt;&gt; can reuse much of the Java infrastructure, including JUnit, mock
&gt; &gt;&gt; &gt;&gt; objects, etc.
&gt; &gt;&gt; &gt;&gt;
&gt; &gt;&gt; &gt;&gt; Best regards,
&gt; &gt;&gt; &gt;&gt; Lance
