&gt; &gt;&gt; &gt;&gt; &gt; Hi!
&gt; &gt;&gt; &gt;&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt;&gt; &gt;&gt; &gt; I think this summarises quite neatly what a couple of people have
&gt; &gt;&gt; &gt;&gt; said,
&gt; &gt;&gt; &gt;&gt; &gt; namely that switching to a dedicated framework from JUnit is only
&gt; &gt;&gt; &gt;&gt; neccessary
&gt; &gt;&gt; &gt;&gt; &gt; if there are quite a few / complicated integration tests.
&gt; &gt;&gt; &gt;&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt;&gt; &gt;&gt; &gt; I happen to agree with this, since introducing more and more
&gt; &gt;&gt; &gt;&gt; frameworks into
&gt; &gt;&gt; &gt;&gt; &gt; your project just for testing will certainly drive many programmers
&gt; &gt;&gt; &gt;&gt; up the
&gt; &gt;&gt; &gt;&gt; &gt; walls. You have to be certain the cost is worth the pay off :) Yet,
&gt; &gt;&gt; &gt;&gt; &gt; especially with user acceptance testing, I have to side with going
&gt; &gt;&gt; &gt;&gt; with a
&gt; &gt;&gt; &gt;&gt; &gt; new framework, if simply for the reason that the client should be
&gt; &gt;&gt; &gt;&gt; able to
&gt; &gt;&gt; &gt;&gt; &gt; read them.
